A clear test often follows Arrange–Act–Assert, but readability matters more than comments naming each phase:

```java
@Test
void rejectsEnrollmentWhenClassIsFull() {
    var courseClass = aCourseClass().withAvailableSeats(0).build();
    when(repository.findById(42L)).thenReturn(Optional.of(courseClass));

    var error = assertThrows(NoSeatAvailable.class,
        () -> service.enroll(42L, studentId));

    assertAll(
        () -> assertEquals(42L, error.courseClassId()),
        () -> verify(repository, never()).save(any())
    );
}
```

Guidelines:
- Name the behavior and condition; do not repeat implementation method names without meaning.
- Keep fixture data minimal but valid. Builders/factories help when models are large.
- Mock a repository, clock or remote client when the unit's contract is the focus. Do not mock value objects or chains of internals merely to force a path.
- Assert returned state, raised errors or durable commands. Verify interactions when the interaction is an observable responsibility, such as publishing an event or not saving invalid state.
- Avoid overspecifying call order or exact internal calls unless order is part of the contract.
- Parameterized tests are useful for a family of equivalent examples; separate tests are clearer for different behavior.

Private methods are normally covered through public behavior. Extraction is justified when the hidden logic is an independent concept—not simply to make a private method directly testable.
